cided to thwart the hack. Look honestly at the situation and consider the issues involved. What would you say to the decision-makers at Netpliance if you had the chance?"</I> <P><B>( </B><A href=http://slashdot.org/articles/00/04/09/095250.shtml><B>Read More...</B></A> | <B><A href=http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=00/04/09/095250&mode=thread&threshold=1>248</A> of <A href=http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=00/04/09/095250&mode=thread&threshold=-1>333</A> </B>comments <B>)</B> <P><TABLE width="99%" cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><TR><TD valign=top bgcolor="#006666"><IMG src="http://images.slashdot.org/slc.gif" width=13 height=16 alt="" align=top><FONT size=4 color="#FFFFFF" face="arial,helvetica"><B>The End Of The Road For Magnetic Hard Drives?</B></FONT></TD> </TR></TABLE><A href="http://slashdot.org/search.pl?topic=tech"><IMG src="http://images.slashdot.org/topics/topictech2.jpg" width=60 height=80 border=0 align=right hspace=20 vspace=10 alt="Technology"></A> <B>Posted by <A href=http://hemos.net>Hemos</A> on Tuesday April 11, @07:31AM</B><BR> <FONT size=2><B>from the reaching-the-technologoical-stop-point dept.</B></FONT><BR> <A href="mailto:speckec@email.nospam.uah.edu">Phase Shifter</A> wrote to us about the limits of <a href=http://sciam.com/2000/0500issue/0500toig.html>conventional hard drives</a>, which <a href=http://www.sciam.com>Scientific American</a> is discussing. The article talks about the history of hard drives, and why sometime soon, due to the limitations of the superparamagnetic effect, we will need to find a new storage type. It's a cool background read on hard drives and what goes into them. <P><B>( </B><A href=http://slashdot.org/articles/00/04/11/0832216.shtml><B>Read More...</B></A> | <B><A href=http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=00/04/11/0832216&mode=thread&threshold=1>107</A> of <A href=http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=00/04/11/0832216&mode=thread&threshold=-1>152</A> </B>comments <B>)</B> <P><TABLE width="99%" cellpadding=0 cell